items.title: The AI that scored 95% — until consultants learned it was AI
items.summary: SAP ran a quiet internal experiment to gauge consultant attitudes toward AI . Five teams were asked to validate answers to more than 1,000 business requirements completed by SAP’s AI co-pilot, Joule for Consultants . The results were striking . The experiment has since become a revealing starting point for SAP's push toward the consultant of 2030: a practitioner who is deeply human, enabled by AI .

items.title: Quilter's AI just designed an 843‑part Linux computer that booted on the first try. Hardware will never be the same.
items.summary: A Los Angeles-based startup has demonstrated what it calls a breakthrough in hardware development: an artificial intelligence system that designed a fully functional Linux computer in one week . The project required just 38.5 hours of human labor compared to the 428 hours that professional PCB designers quoted for the same task . The announcement shines a light on an unglamorous but critical chokepoint in technology development: printed circuit board layout .

items.title: How Hud's runtime sensor cut triage time from 3 hours to 10 minutes
items.summary: Hackers are hitting a wall when AI-generated code reaches production, says Hud . Traditional monitoring tools struggle to provide granular, function-level data AI agents need to understand how code behaves in complex production environments . Hud's eponymous sensor runs alongside production code, automatically tracking how every function behaves, giving developers a heads-up on what actually occurs in deployment .
